# Entry in std::collections::hash\_map - Rust

```
pub enum Entry<'a, K: 'a, V: 'a> {
    Occupied(OccupiedEntry<'a, K, V>),
    Vacant(VacantEntry<'a, K, V>),
}
```

Expand description

A view into a single entry in a map, which may either be vacant or occupied.

This `enum` is constructed from the [`entry`](about:blank/struct.HashMap.html#method.entry "method std::collections::hash_map::HashMap::entry") method on [`HashMap`](struct.HashMap.html "struct std::collections::hash_map::HashMap").

An occupied entry.

[Â§](#variant.Vacant)1.0.0

1.0.0 Â· [source](about:blank/src/std/collections/hash/map.rs.html#2639-2644)

Ensures a value is in the entry by inserting the default if empty, and returns a mutable reference to the value in the entry.

##### [Â§](#examples)Examples

```
use std::collections::HashMap;

let mut map: HashMap<&str, u32> = HashMap::new();

map.entry("poneyland").or_insert(3);
assert_eq!(map["poneyland"], 3);

*map.entry("poneyland").or_insert(10) *= 2;
assert_eq!(map["poneyland"], 6);
```

1.0.0 Â· [source](about:blank/src/std/collections/hash/map.rs.html#2663-2668)

Ensures a value is in the entry by inserting the result of the default function if empty, and returns a mutable reference to the value in the entry.

##### [Â§](#examples-1)Examples

```
use std::collections::HashMap;

let mut map = HashMap::new();
let value = "hoho";

map.entry("poneyland").or_insert_with(|| value);

assert_eq!(map["poneyland"], "hoho");
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::collections::HashMap;%0A++++%0A++++let+mut+map+=+HashMap::new();%0A++++let+value+=+%22hoho%22;%0A++++%0A++++map.entry(%22poneyland%22).or_insert_with(%7C%7C+value);%0A++++%0A++++assert_eq!(map%5B%22poneyland%22%5D,+%22hoho%22);%0A%7D&edition=2021)

1.50.0 Â· [source](about:blank/src/std/collections/hash/map.rs.html#2690-2698)

Ensures a value is in the entry by inserting, if empty, the result of the default function. This method allows for generating key-derived values for insertion by providing the default function a reference to the key that was moved during the `.entry(key)` method call.

The reference to the moved key is provided so that cloning or copying the key is unnecessary, unlike with `.or_insert_with(|| ... )`.

##### [Â§](#examples-2)Examples

```
use std::collections::HashMap;

let mut map: HashMap<&str, usize> = HashMap::new();

map.entry("poneyland").or_insert_with_key(|key| key.chars().count());

assert_eq!(map["poneyland"], 9);
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::collections::HashMap;%0A++++%0A++++let+mut+map:+HashMap%3C%26str,+usize%3E+=+HashMap::new();%0A++++%0A++++map.entry(%22poneyland%22).or_insert_with_key(%7Ckey%7C+key.chars().count());%0A++++%0A++++assert_eq!(map%5B%22poneyland%22%5D,+9);%0A%7D&edition=2021)

1.26.0 Â· [source](about:blank/src/std/collections/hash/map.rs.html#2741-2752)

Provides in-place mutable access to an occupied entry before any potential inserts into the map.

##### [Â§](#examples-4)Examples

```
use std::collections::HashMap;

let mut map: HashMap<&str, u32> = HashMap::new();

map.entry("poneyland")
   .and_modify(|e| { *e += 1 })
   .or_insert(42);
assert_eq!(map["poneyland"], 42);

map.entry("poneyland")
   .and_modify(|e| { *e += 1 })
   .or_insert(42);
assert_eq!(map["poneyland"], 43);
```
